04265nam a22005055i 9780226381176DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016005058  a97802263811767 a10.7208/97802263811762doi  a(DE-B1597)550274  a(OCoLC)959554480  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aQH513b.V65 2016 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a612.762231 aVogel, Steven, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhy the Wheel Is Round :bMuscles, Technology, and How We Make Things Move /cSteven Vogel. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b81 halftones, 64 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Circling Bodies -- t2. Wheels and Wagons -- t3. Turning Points— and Pots -- t4. Going in Circles -- t5. Or Being Encircled -- t6. Grabbing Again and Again -- t7. Turning and Unturning -- t8. The True Crank -- t9. Spinning Fibers -- t10. A Few More Turns -- t11. Rolling Back Rotation -- tAppendix: Making Models -- tNotes -- tReferences0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThere is no part of our bodies that fully rotates—be it a wrist or ankle or arm in a shoulder socket, we are made to twist only so far. And yet there is no more fundamental human invention than the wheel—a rotational mechanism that accomplishes what our physical form cannot. Throughout history, humans have developed technologies powered by human strength, complementing the physical abilities we have while overcoming our weaknesses. Providing a unique history of the wheel and other rotational devices—like cranks, cranes, carts, and capstans—Why the Wheel Is Round examines the contraptions and tricks we have devised in order to more efficiently move—and move through—the physical world. Steven Vogel combines his engineering expertise with his remarkable curiosity about how things work to explore how wheels and other mechanisms were, until very recently, powered by the push and pull of the muscles and skeletal systems of humans and other animals. Why the Wheel Is Round explores all manner of treadwheels, hand-spikes, gears, and more, as well as how these technologies diversified into such things as hand-held drills and hurdy-gurdies. Surprisingly, a number of these devices can be built out of everyday components and materials, and Vogel’s accessible and expansive book includes instructions and models so that inspired readers can even attempt to make their own muscle-powered technologies, like trebuchets and ballista. Appealing to anyone fascinated by the history of mechanics and technology as well as to hobbyists with home workshops, Why the Wheel Is Round offers a captivating exploration of our common technological heritage based on the simple concept of rotation. From our leg muscles powering the gears of a bicycle to our hands manipulating a mouse on a roller ball, it will be impossible to overlook the amazing feats of innovation behind our daily devices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aBiomechanics. 0aRotational motion. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226381176423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226381176.jpg  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles